office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui in tu carittis exemplum, ad fidlium redemptinem sanctum Petrum Ecclsiam tuam nova prole fcundare divinitus docusti: ipsus nobis intercessine concde; a peccti servitute solutis, in clsti ptria perptua libertte gaudre: Qui vivis et regnas.

O GOD, by whose inspiration the holy Peter increased the family of thy Church with a new order for the redemption of the faithful, following therein the example of thine own divine charity; mercifully grant, that, by the power of his intercession, we may be loosed from the bonds of sin, and enjoy everlasting freedom in our heavenly country. Who livest.

office:text.text:p: Commemoration is also made of St. Agnes, Virgin and Martyr, at Lauds:

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Ecce, quod concupvi, * jam vdeo: quod spervi jam teneo: ipsi sum juncta in clis, quem in terris psita, tota devotine dilxi.
Ant. Behold, now I see * that which I have desired; now I possess that for which I have hoped: now am I united in Heaven to him whom I have love with my whole heart upon earth.
V. Diffsa est grtia in lbiis tuis.
R. Proptrea benedxit te Deus in trnum.
V. Grace is poured abroad in thy lips.
R. Therefore hath God blessed thee for ever.

OMNPOTENS sempiterne Deus, qui infirma mundi eligis, ut fortia quque confndas: concde proptius; ut, qui bet Agnetis Vrginis et Mrtyris tu solemnia colimus, ejus apud te patrocinia sentimus. Per Dminum.

ALMIGHTY and everlasting God who choosest the weak things of the world to confound the strong; mercifully grant that we, who keep the solemn feast of thy Virgin and Martyr, the blessed Agnes, may feel the benefit of her intercession with thee. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Ep., Conf. et Eccl. Doct. - III classis - Jan. 29
Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui ad animrum saltem betum Franciscum Confessrem tuum atque Pontficem mnibus mnia factum esse volusti: concde proptius; ut carittis tu dulcdine perfusi, ejus dirigntibus monitis ac suffragntibus meritis, trna gaudia consequmur. Per Dminum.

O GOD, by whose gracious the blessed Francis, thy Confessor and Bishop, became all things unto all men for the saving of their souls; mercifully grant that, being filled with the sweetness of thy love, we may, through the guidance of his counsels, and by the aid of his merits, attain unto the joys of the life everlasting. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Virginis et Martyris - III classis - Jan. 30
Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Virgins.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui inter cetera potnti tu miracula tiam in sexu fragili victriam martyrii contulsti: concde proptius; ut, qui bet Martin Vrginis et Mrtyris tu nataltia colimus, per ejus ad te exempla gradimur. Per Dminum.

O GOD, amidst the wondrous work of thy Divine power, thou hast granted the victory of martyrdom even to the weaker sex; mercifully grant that all who keep the Birthday of thy blessed Virgin and Martyr Martina, may, through her example, draw nearer to thee. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.

table:table-cell.text:p: FRATRES: Qui gloritur, in Dmino gloritur. Non enim qui sepsum commndat, ille probtus est; sed quem Deus commndat.
R. Deo grtias.
BROTHERS: he that glorieth, let him glory in the Lord. For not he who commendeth himself, is approved, but he, whom God commendeth.
R. Thanks be to God.
Tu natale solum prtege, tu bon
Da pacis rquiem Christiadum plagis;
Armrum strepitus, et fera prlia
In fines age Thracios.
Protect thy native City, Spirit blest! / And give to Christendom sweet days of peace; / Bid the shrill trumpet, and the shock of war, Within her realms to cease.
Et regum socians agmina sub crucis
Vxillo, Solymas nxibus xime,
Vindexque innocui snguinis hosticum
Robur funditus erue.
And gathering her kings beneath the Cross, / Regain Jerusalem from our proud foe; / Avenge the innocent blood and the proud strength / Of Islam overthrow.
Tu nostrum columen, tu decus inclytum,
Nostrrum obsequium rspice mntium;
Rom vota libens excipe, qu pio
Te ritu canit, et colit.
O Pillar and defence of thine own Rome! / Her boast, her crown, her glory, and her praise! / This day thy memory she keeps; accept / The solemn rite she pays.
A nobis abigas lubrica gaudia,
Tu, qui Martyribus dexter ades, Deus
Une et Trine: tuis da fmulis jubar,
Quo clemens animos beas. Amen.
Expel false worldly joys; and fill us Lord, / With thy irradiating beam divine; / Who with the suffering martyrs present art, / Great Godhead one and trine. Amen.
V. Diffsa est grtia in lbiis tuis.
R. Proptrea benedxit te Deus in trnum.
V. Grace is poured abroad in thy lips.
R. Therefore hath God blessed thee for ever.
Ant. Smile est regnum clrum * hmini negotiatri qurnti bonas margartas: invnta una pretisa, dedit mnia sua, et comparvit eam.
Ant. The kingdom of heaven is like to * a merchant seeking good pearls: when he finds one pearl of great price, he gives all that he has and buys it.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
Little Chapter, Hymn & Versicle as at Lauds.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Veni, Sponsa Christi, * ccipe cornam, quam tibi Dminus prparvit in trnum.
Ant. Come, Bride of Christ, * and take the everlasting crown which the Lord hath prepared for thee.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui sanctum Jonnem Confessrem tuum adolescntium patrem et magistrum excitsti, ac per eum, auxiliatrice Vrgine Mara, novas in Ecclsia tua famlias florescere volusti: concde, qusumus; ut eodem carittis igne succnsi, nimas qurere, tibique soli servire valemus. Per Dminum.

O GOD, Thou hast raised up Saint John, thy Confessor, to be a father and teacher of youth, and hast willed that through him, with the help of the Virgin Mary, new families should flourish in thy Church; grant, we beseech thee, that inflamed by the same fire of love, we may labour to seek souls and serve thee alone. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Ep. et Mart. - III classis - Feb. 1
Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of one Martyr.

table:table-cell.text:p: INFIRMITTEM nostram rspice, omnpotens Deus: et, quia pondus propri actinis gravat, beti Ignatii Mrtyris tui atque Pontificis intercssio glorisa nos prtegat. Per Dminum.

ALMIGHTY God, mercifully look upon our infirmity; and because the burden of our own actions does sorely hinder us, may the glorious intercession of blessed Ignatius, thy martyr and bishop, ever protect us. Through our Lord.

OMNPOTENS sempiterne Deus, majesttem tuam supplices exormus: ut, sicut unignitus Flius tuus hodirna die cum nostr carnis substntia in templo est prsenttus; ita nos fcias purifictis tibi mntibus prsentari. Per emdem Dminum.

O ALMIGHTY and eternal God, we suppliants beseech thy Majesty that, as thine only-begotten Son was this day presented in the temple in the substance of our flesh, so thou wouldst grant us to be presented, purified in mind and heart, to thee. Through the same.

office:text.text:p: If the feast occurs on Sunday, it is celebrated as feast of the I class:

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant 1. O admirbile commercium: * Creator generis humani, animtum corpus sumens, de Vrgine nasci digntus est: et procdens homo sine semine, largitus est nobis suam Deittem.
Ant 1. O admirable interchange! * The Creator of man, assuming a living body, deigned to be born of a Virgin, and becoming man, without mans aid, bestowed on us his divinity.

office:text.text:p: Psalms as in Common of the B.V.M.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant 2. Quando natus es * ineffabliter ex Vrgine, tunc implet sunt Scriptur: sicut plvia in vellus descendsti, ut salvum fceres genus humanum: te laudamus, Deus noster.
Ant 2. When thou was born * ineffably of the Virgin, the Scriptures were fulfilled. As dew upon Gedeons fleece, thou camest down to save mankind. O Lord our God, we praise thee.
Ant 3. Rubum, quem viderat Myses * incombustum, conservatam agnovimus tuam laudbilem virginittem: Dei Gnitrix, intercde pro nobis.
Ant 3. In the bush seen by Moses * as burning yet unconsumed, we recognise the preservation of thy glorious virginity. O Mother of God, intercede for us.
Ant 4. Germinvit radix Jesse, * orta est stella ex Jacob, Virgo pperit Salvatrem: te laudamus, Deus noster.
Ant 4. The Root of Jesse hath budded; * the Star hath risen out of Jacob; a Virgin hath brought forth the Saviour. O Lord our God, we praise thee.
Ant 5. Ecce Mara gnuit * nobis Salvatrem, quem Jonnes videns exclamvit, dicens: Ecce Agnus Dei, ecce qui tollit peccta mundi. Allelja.
Ant 5. Lo! Mary hath brought forth * a Saviour unto us, whom John seeing, exclaimed: Behold the Lamb of God! Behold him that taketh away the sins of the world, alleluia.
ECCE ego mitto Angelum meum, et prparbit viam ante fciem meam. Et statim vniet ad templum sanctum suum Dominator, quem vos quritis, et Angelus Testamenti, quem vos vultis.
R. Deo grtias.
BEHOLD I send my angel, and he shall prepare the way before my face. And presently the Lord, whom you seek, and the Angel of the Testament, whom you desire, shall come to his holy temple.
R. Thanks be to God.

office:text.text:p: Hymn as in Common of B.V.M., with the following responsory:

table:table-cell.text:p: V. Responsum accpit Simeon a Spritu Sancto.
R. Non visurum se mortem, nisi vidret Christum, Domini.
V. Simeon received an answer from the Holy Ghost.
R. That he should not see death, until he had seen Christ the Lord.
Ant. Senex * Puerum portabat, Puer autem senem regbat: quem virgo pperit, et post partum virgo permansit: ipsum quem gnuit, adorvit.
Ant. The old man * held the child in his arms, but the child was the old mans Lord. Him whom a virgin brought forth, remaining a virgin still, that same did she adore.
Ant 1. Simeon justus * et timortus exspectbat redemptinem Isral, et Spritus Sanctus erat in eo.
Ant 1. Simeon, a just man, * and devout, waited for the redemption of Israel, and the Holy Ghost was in him.

office:text.text:p: Psalms as in Sunday Lauds I

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant 2. Responsum accpit Simeon * a Spritu Sancto, non visurum se mortem, nisi vidret Dminum.
Ant 2. Simeon received an answer * from the Holy Ghost, that he should not see death until he had seen the Lord.
Ant 3. Accpiens Simeon * Puerum in mnibus, grtias agens benedxit Dminum.
Ant 3. Simeon taking * the child into his arms, gave thanks and blessed the Lord.
Ant 4. Lumen ad revelatinem Gntium, * et glriam plebis tu Isral.
Ant 4. A light to the revealing of the Gentiles, * and the glory of thy people Israel.
Ant 5. Obtulrunt * pro eo Dmino par turturum aut duos pullos columbarum.
Ant 5. They offered * for him unto the Lord a pair of turtle doves, or two young pigeons.

office:text.text:p: Little Chapter as in I Vespers.
Hymn and responsory as in Common of B.V.M.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Cum inducerent * perum Jesum parntes ejus, accpit eum Simeon in ulnas suas, et benedxit Deum, dicens: Nunc dimittis servum tuum in pace.
Ant. And when his parents brought in * the child Jesus, Simeon took him into his arms, and blessed God, and said: Now thou dost dismiss thy servant in peace.

office:text.text:p: At the Little Hours, the psalms and antiphons of the current feria.
If this feast occurs on the Sunday of Septuagesima, Sexagesima, or Quinquagesima, the antiphons at the Little Hours are taken from Lauds, with the psalms of Sunday. At Prime, Pss. 117, 118i & 118ii.
In the Brief Respond, the following Versicle is said:

table:table-cell.text:p: V. Qui natus es de Mara Vrgine.
V. Who was born of the Virgin Mary.

office:text.text:p: Little Chapter as in I Vespers.

table:table-cell.text:p: V. Deus omnpotens * Prcinxit me virtte.
V. God Almighty * hath girt me with strength.
R. Deus omnpotens...
R. God Almighty...
V. Et psuit immacultam viam meam.
V. And made my way immaculate.
R. Prcinxit me virtte.
R. Hath girt me with strength.
V. Glria Patri...Sancto.
V. Glory be...Holy Spirit.
R. Deus omnpotens...
R. God Almighty...
V. In hoc cognvi, quniam volusti me.
V. By this I know, that thou hast had a good will for me.
R. Quniam non gaudbit inimcus meus super me.
R. Because my enemy shall not rejoice over me.
PORTA hc clausa erit, non aperitur, et vir non intrbit per eam, quniam Dminus Deus Isral ingrssus est per eam: eritque clausa principi. Princeps ipse sedbit in ea.
R. Deo grtias.

THIS gate shall be shut, it shall not be opened, and no man shall pass through it: because the Lord the God of Israel hath entered in by it, and it shall be shut for the prince. The prince himself shall sit in it
R. Thanks be to God.
V. In hoc cognvi, * Quniam volusti me.
V. By this I know, * That thou hast had a good will for me.
R. In hoc cognvi...
R. By this I know...
V. Quniam non gaudbit inimcus meus super me.
V. Because my enemy shall not rejoice over me.
R. Quniam volusti me.
R. That thou hast had a good will for me.
V. Glria Patri...Sancto.
V. Glory be...Holy Spirit.
R. In hoc cognvi...
R. By this I know...
V. Exaltbo te, Dmine, quniam suscepsti me.
V. I will extol thee, O Lord, for thou hast upheld me.
R. Nec delectsti inimcos meos super me.
R. And hast not made my enemies to rejoice over me.
SIGNUM magnum appruit in clo: Mlier amcta sole, et luna sub pdibus ejus, et in cpite ejus corna stellrum duodecim.
R. Deo grtias.
AND a great sign appeared in heaven: A woman clothed with the sun, and the moon under her feet, and on her head a crown of twelve stars.
R. Thanks be to God.
V. Exaltbo te, Dmine, * Quniam suscepsti me.
V. I will extol thee, O Lord, * For thou hast upheld me.
R. Exaltbo te...
R. I will extol thee...
V. Nec delectsti inimcos meos super me.
V. And hast not made my enemies to rejoice over me.
R. Quniam suscepsti me.
R. For thou hast upheld me.
V. Glria Patri...Sancto.
V. Glory be...Holy Spirit.
R. Exaltbo te...
R. I will extol thee...
V. Immaculta Conceptio tua, Dei Gnitrix Virgo.
V. Maiden Mother of god, thy stainless conception.
R. Gaudium annuntivit univrso mundo.
R. Was a message of joy to the whole world.

office:text.text:p: Psalms as in Common of B.V.M.
Little Chapter as in I Vespers.
Hymn as in Common of B.V.M., with the responsory from I Vespers.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Hdie egressa est * virga de radce Jesse: hdie sine ulla peccti labe concepta est Mara: hdie contrtum est ab ea caput serpntis antiqui, allelja.
Ant. This day is a rod * sprung from the root of Jesse: this day is Mary conceived without any stain of sin: this day hath she bruised the head of the old serpent, alleluia.
Ant. Qui odit * nimam suam in hoc mundo, in vitam trnam custdit eam.
Ant. He that hateth * his life in this world, keepeth it to life eternal.
V. Justus ut palma florbit.
R. Sicut cedrus Lbani multiplicbitur.
V. The just shall flourish like the palm tree.
R. He shall grow up like the cedar of Libanus.
DEUS, qui nos beti Blasii Mrtyris tui atque Pontificis annua solemnitate ltificas: concde proptius; ut, cujus nataltia colimus, de ejsdem tiam protectine gaudemus. Per Dminum.

O GOD, who dost gladden us by the yearly solemnity of blessed Blaise, thy Martyr and Bishop; mercifully grant that, as we celebrate his festival, we may also rejoice in his protection. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Ep. et Conf. - III classis - Feb. 4
Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui in Ecclsia tua, nova semper instauras exempla virttum : da ppulo tuo beti Andre Confessris tui atque Pontificis ita sequi vestgia ; ut assequtur et prmia. Per Dminum.

O GOD, who dost continually raise up in thy Church new examples of virtue, grant unto thy people so to follow in the footsteps of thy blessed Bishop and Confessor Andrew that they may also attain unto a like reward. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Virginis et Martyris - III classis - Feb. 5

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS qui inter cetera potnti tu miracula tiam in sexu fragili victriam martyrii contulsti : concde proptius ; ut, qui bet Agath Vrginis et Mrtyris tu nataltia colimus, per ejus ad te exempla gradimur. Per Dminum.

O GOD, who among other wondrous works of thy power hast bestowed the victory of martyrdom even on the weaker sex; mercifully grant that we who celebrate the heavenly birthday of blessed Agatha thy Virgin and Martyr, may, by following her example, advance in the way that leadeth unto thee. Through our Lord.
Ant 1. Quis es tu, * qui vensti ad me curare vulnera mea? Ego sum Apstolus Christi : nihil in me dubites, filia.
Ant 1. Who art thou * that comest unto me to heal my wounds? I am the Apostle of Christ, have no suspicion of me, my daughter.

office:text.text:p: Psalms as in Sunday Lauds I

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant 2. Medicinam carnalem * corpori meo numquam exhibui, sed habeo Dminum Jesum Christum, qui solo sermne restaurat universa.
Ant 2. I have never applied * a medicine of this earth to my body, but I have my Lord Jesus Christ, who by his word alone restoreth all things.
Ant 3. Gratias tibi ago, * Dmine Jesu Christe, quia memor es mei, et missti ad me Apstolum tuum curare vulnera mea.
Ant 3. I give thee thanks, * O Lord Jesus Christ, because thou art mindful of me, and hast sent thine Apostle unto me to heal my wounds.
Ant 4. Benedico te, * Pater Dmini mei Jesu Christi, quia per Apstolum tuum mamillam meam meo pctori restituisti.
Ant 4. I bless thee, * O Father of my Lord Jesus Christ, because by thine Apostle thou hast restored my breast to my bosom.
Ant 5. Qui me digntus est * ab omni plaga curare, et mamillam meam meo pctori restitere, ipsum invoco Deum vivum.
Ant 5. He that hath vouchsafed * to heal all my wounds and to restore my breast to my bosom, upon him do I call, the living God.
CONFITBOR tibi, Dmine, Rex, et collaudbo te Deum Salvatrem meum. Confitbor nmini tuo : quniam adjtor et protctor factus es mihi, et libersti corpus meum a perditione.
R. Deo grtias.

I will give glory to thee, O Lord, O King, and I will praise thee, O God my Saviour. I will give glory to thy name: for thou hast been a helper and protector to me. And hast preserved my body from destruction
R. Thanks be to God.

office:text.text:p: Hymn as in Common of Virgins.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Paganrum * multitdo fgiens ad seplcrum Vrginis, tulrunt velum ejus contra ignem : ut comprobaret Dminus, quod a periculis incendii meritis bet Agath Mrtyris su eos liberaret.

Ant. The heathen * multitude fleeing to the tomb of the virgin, took thence her veil as a defence against the rolling flames: for the Lord would show that by the merits of his blessed Martyr Agatha he would deliver them from the perils of fire.

office:text.text:p: At the Little Hours, psalms and antiphons of the current feria.
Brief Respond as in Common of Virgins.

table:table-cell.text:p: LIBERSTI me secndum multitdinem misericrdi nminis tui a rugintibus, prpartis ad escam, de mnibus qurntium nimam meam, et de multis tribulatinibus qu circumdedrunt me.
R. Deo grtias.

THOU hast delivered me, according to the multitude of the mercy of thy name, from them that did roar, prepared to devour. Out of the hands of them that sought my life, and from the gates of afflictions, which compassed me about:
R. Thanks be to God.

office:text.text:p: Brief Respond as in Common of Virgins.

table:table-cell.text:p: LAUDBIT usque ad mortem nima mea Dminum, quniam eruis sustinntes te, et liberas eos de manu angusti, Dmine, Deus noster.
R. Deo grtias.
MY SOUL shall praise the Lord even to death. How thou deliverest them that wait for thee, O Lord, and savest them out of the hands of the nations.
R. Thanks be to God.

office:text.text:p: Brief Respond as in Common of Virgins.
Psalms as in Sunday Vespers, but in the last place Ps. 147, Lauda, Jersalem.
Hymn as in Common of Virgins.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Stans beta Agatha * in mdio crceris, expansis mnibus orbat ad Dminum : Dmine Jesu Christe, magister bone, grtias tibi ago, qui me fecsti vincere tormnta carnficum : jube me, Dmine, ad tuam immarcescbilem glriam feliciter pervenre.

Ant. The blessed Agatha, standing in the prison, with outstretched hands, prayed unto the Lord: O Lord Jesus Christ, good Master, I give thanks unto thee who hast enabled me to overcome the tortures of the executioners: bid me now, O Lord, come happily unto thine unfading glory.

office:text.text:p: Ep. et Conf. - III classis - July 7

table:table-cell.text:p: OMNPOTENS sempiterne Deus, qui Slavoni gentes per betos Confessores tuos atque Pontifices Cyrillum et Methdium ad agnitinem tui nminis venre tribusti: prsta; ut, quorum festivitate glorimur, erum consrtio copulemur. Per Dminum.

O ALMIGHTY, eternal God, who, by means of thy blessed Confessors and Bishops Cyril and Methodius, wert pleased to bring the people of Slavonia to the knowledge of thy name; grant that we, who rejoice in celebrating their festival, may be united with them in eternal fellowship. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and antiphons of the current feria.

table:table-cell.text:p: ECCE sacrdos magnus, qui in dibus suis plcuit Deo, et invntus est justus: et in tmpore iracndi factus est reconcilitio.
R. Deo grtias.
BEHOLD a great priest who in his days pleased God, and was found righteous; and in the time of wrath he was made a reconciliation.
R. Thanks be to God.
Lux o decora ptri
Slavisque amica gntibus,
Salvete, fratres: annuo
Vos effermus cntico.
O Light all beauteous of the Fatherland, and of the Sclavonic race benignant Ray,Brethren, all hail! To you, our yearly canticle we bring;
Quos Roma plaudens excipit,
Complexa mater flios,
Auget corna prsulum
Novoque firmat robore.
Whom Rome applauding, did receive, as Mother pressing to her heart, loved sons,she upon your brow, the Bishops diadem doth place, and girdeth with new strength!
Terras ad usque barbaras
Inferre Christum pergitis;
Quot vanus error luserat,
Almo repltis lmine.
Ye penetrate to furthest barbarous lands, to bring them Christ. Where error vain did darkly play, ye there pour in the radiance of fair light.
Noxis soluta pctora
Ardor supernus abripit;
Muttur horror veprium
In sanctittis flosculos.
On hearts unshackled from the grasp of ill, doth heavenly ardour seize; thorns horrid aspect now is changed for flowers of holiness.
Et nunc serena Clitum
Locti in aula, supplici
Adeste voto: Slavicas
Servate gentes Numini.
Then deign, O ye who reign secure in courts celestial, to turn unto our suppliant prayer: Preserve unto God the Sclavonic people.
Errore mersos unicum
Ovile Christi congreget;
Factis vitis mula
Fides virescat pulchrior.
May the one Fold of Christ inclose those in error plunged: emulating the deeds of their forefathers, may faith revive more beauteous still.
Tu nos, beta Trnitas,
Clsti amre concita,
Patrumque natos inclyta
Da persequi vestgia. Amen.
O Thou, Most Blessed Trinity, spur us on, by heavenly Love, and grant that the sons may follow in the noble footprints of their sires! Amen.
V. Sapintiam Sanctrum narrent ppuli.
R. Et laudem erum nntiet Ecclsia.
V. Let the people show forth the wisdom of the Saints.
R. And let the Church declare their praise.
Ant. In sanctitte * et justtia servirunt Dmino omnibus dibus suis: deo stolam glri nduit illos Dminus, Deus Isral.
Ant. In holiness * and justice they served the Lord all the days of their life; therefore the Lord, the God of Israel, clothed them with a robe of glory.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor Bishop.
Psalms and antiphons of the current feria.

table:table-cell.text:p: Sdibus cli nitidis receptos
Dcite athletas geminos, fidles;
Slavic duplex columen decusque
Dcite gentis.
Sing, O ye Faithful, sing two Athletes, Brothers, received unto their brilliant thrones celestial; sing the two-fold strength and glory of the Sclavonic race.
Hos amor fratres socivit unus,
Unaque abduxit pietas ermo,
Ferre quo multis celerent bet
Pignora vit.
One Love these Brethren did together bind in union sweet, and one the tender pity that did them from their solitude urge forth; they haste to bear to many, the pledge of blessed Life.
Luce, qu templis superis renidet,
Bulgaros complent, Moravos, Bohemos;
Mox feras turmas numerosa Petro
Agmina ducunt.
Bulgarians, Moravians, and Bohemians they fill with Light, that beams resplendent in supernal temples; to Peter, soon, these savage hordes they lead, a numerous throng.
Debitam cincti meritis cornam,
Pergite o flecti lcrimis precantum;
Prisca vos Slavis opus est datores
Dona tueri.

Your brow encircled by the well earned crown of merits, Oh! do ye still continue to be ever moved by suppliants tears; needful indeed it is that ye protect your former gifts bestowed upon the Sclaves!
Quque vos clamat generosa tellus
Servet trn fdei nitrem:
Qu dedit princeps, dabit ipsa semper
Roma saltem.
May the generous soil, that crieth unto you, preserve the pure brightness of eternal Faith: Rome which first in the beginning gave, will ever give salvation to that land.
Gentis human Sator et Redemptor,
Qui bonus nobis bona cuncta prbes,
Sint tibi grates, tibi sit per omne
Glria sclum. Amen.
O Creator and Redeemer of the human race, who in thy goodness, givest us all good things, to thee, be thanksgiving, to thee be glory for ever and ever. Amen.
V. Sacerdtes tui induntur justtiam.
R. Et Sancti tui exsltent.
V. Let thy priests be clothed with justice.
R. And let thy saints rejoice.
Ant. Isti sunt * viri sancti facti amci Dei, divn verittis prconio gloriosi: lingu erum claves cli fact sunt.
Ant. These are * the holy men become the friends of God and made glorious by the preaching of divine truth; their tongues have become the keys of heaven.

text:list-item.text:h: July 8 - St. Elizabeth, Queen of Portugal

table:table-cell.text:p: CLEMENTSSIME Deus, qui, betam Elisabeth regnam, inter ceteras egregias dotes, bellici furoris sedndi prrogativa decorsti: da nobis, ejus intercessine; post mortalis vit, quam suppliciter petimus, pacem, ad trna gaudia pervenre. Per Dminum.

O MOST merciful God, who, among other rare gifts, didst adorn the blessed Queen Elizabeth with a singular grace for quelling the rage of war; grant through her intercession that, after enjoying in this mortal life the peace for which we humbly bet, we may attain unto eternal joys. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and antiphons of the current feria.

table:table-cell.text:p: MULEREM fortem quis invniet? Procul et de ltimis fnibus prtium ejus. Confdit in ea cor viri sui, et spliis non indigbit.
R. Deo grtias.
WHO shall find a valiant woman? far and from the uttermost coasts is the price of her. The heart of her husband trusteth in her, and he shall have no need of spoils.
R. Thanks be to God.
Opes decusque regium reliqueras,
Elisabeth, Dei dicta numini:
Recepta nunc bearis inter Angelos;
Libens ab hstium tuere nos dolis.
Riches and regal throne, for Christs dear sake, / True Saint, thou didst despise; / Amid the angels seated now in bliss, / Oh, help us from the skies!
Pri, viamque, dux saltis, ndica:
Sequemur: O sit una mens fidlium,
Odor bonus sit omnis actio, tuis
Id innuit rosis oprta critas.
Guide us; and fill our days with perfume sweet / Of loving word and deed; / So teaches us thy beauteous charity, / By fragrant roses hid.
Beta critas, in arce siderum
Potens locare nos per omne sculum:
Patrique, Filique summa glria,
Tibique laus perennis, alme Spritus. Amen.
O Charity! what power is thine! by thee / Above the stars we soar; / In thee be purest praise to Father, Son, / And Spirit, evermore. Amen.
V. Meritis et prcibus bet Elisabeth.
R. Propitius esto, Dmine, ppulo tuo.
V. By the merits and prayers of blessed Elizabeth.
R. Be propitious, O Lord, to thy people.
Ant. Tu glria Jerusalem, * tu lttia Isral, tu honorificntia ppuli tui.
Ant. Thou art the glory of Jerusalem, * thou art the joy of Israel, thou art the honour of thy people.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Holy Women.
Psalms and antiphons of the current feria.

table:table-cell.text:p: Domare cordis mpetus Elisabeth
Fortis, inopsque Deo
Servire, regno prtulit.
Pure, meek, with soul serene,
Sweeter to her it was to serve unseen
Her God, than reign a queen.
En fulgidis recepta cli sdibus,
Sidereque domus
Ditta sanctis gaudiis.
Now far above our sight,
Enthroned upon the star-paved azure height,
She reigns in realms of light;
Nunc regnat inter clites betior,
Et premit astra, docens
Qu vera sint regni bona.
So long as time shall flow,
Teaching to all who sit on thrones below,
The good that power can do.
Patri potstas, Filique glria,
Perpetuumque decus
Tibi sit, alme Spritus. Amen.
To God , the Sire and Son
And Paraclete, be glory, Trine in One,
While endless ages run. Amen.
V. Ora pro nobis, beta Elisabeth.
R. Ut digni efficimur promissinibus Christi.
V. Pray for us, O blessed Elisabeth.
R. That we may be worthy of the promises of Christ.
Ant. Elisabeth, * pacis et ptri mater, in clo trimphans, dona nobis pacem.
Ant. Elizabeth, * mother of peace and of thy country, now triumphant in heaven, give us peace.

text:list-item.text:h: July 10 - Seven Brothers, and Ss. Rufina and Secunda

office:text.text:p: Virg. et Mart. - III classis - July 10
Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Martyrs.

table:table-cell.text:p: PRSTA, qusumus, omnpotens Deus: ut, qui glorisos Mrtyres fortes in sua confessine cognvimus, pios apud te in nostra intercessine sentimus. Per Dminum.

GRANT, we beseech thee, O almighty God, that we who acknowledge the glorious Martyrs to have been valiant in their confession of thy faith, may now experience their compassion by their intercession for us with thee. Through our Lord.
Ant. Qui odit * nimam suam in hoc mundo, in vitam trnam custdit eam.
Ant. He that hateth * his life in this world, keepeth it to life eternal.
V. Justus ut palma florbit.
R. Sicut cedrus Lbani multiplicbitur.
V. The just shall flourish like the palm tree.
R. He shall grow up like the cedar of Libanus.
GREGEM tuum, Pastor trne, plactus intnde: et per betum Pium Mrtyrem tuum atque Summum Pontficem, perptua protectine custodi; quem totus Ecclsi prstitsti esse pastrem. Per Dminum.

O ETERNAL Shepherd, do thou look with favor upon thy flock. Guard and keep it for evermore through blessed Pius, thy Martyr and Supreme Pontiff, whom thou didst choose to be the chief shepherd of the whole Church. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: INTERCSSIO nos, qusumus, Dmine, beti Jonnis Abbtis commendet : ut, quod nostris meritis non valemus, ejus patrocinio assequmur. Per Dminum.

MAY THE intercession, O Lord, we beseech thee, of the blessed Abbot John commend us unto thee, that what by our own merits we are not worthy to receive, we may obtain by his patronage. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Commemoration is made of Ss. Nabor and Felix, Mm., at Lauds:

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Vestri caplli cpitis * omnes numerti sunt: nolte timre: multis passribus melires estis vos.
Ant. The very hairs of your head * are all numbered; fear not: you are of more value than many sparrows.
V. Exsultbunt Sancti in glria.
R. Ltabntur in cublibus suis.
V. The Saints shall rejoice in glory.
R. They shall be joyful in their beds.
PRSTA, qusumus, Dmine : ut, sicut nos sanctrum Mrtyrum turum Naboris et Felicis nataltia celebranda non dserunt ; ita jugiter suffragiis comitntur. Per Dminum.
GRANT, we beseech thee, O Lord, that, as we fail not to celebrate the heavenly birthday of thy holy Martyrs Nabor and Felix, so they may unceasingly help us by their prayers. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Ep., Conf. et Eccl. Doct. - III classis - July 14
Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui ppulo tuo trn saltis betum Bonaventram ministrum tribusti: prsta, qusumus; ut, quem Doctrem vit habimus in terris, intercessrem habre meremur in clis. Per Dminum.

O GOD, who didst give blessed Bonaventure to thy people to be a minister of eternal salvation; grant, we beseech thee, that we may deserve to have him for an intercessor in heaven whom we have had as a teacher of life on Earth. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui hodirna die betum Henricum Confessrem tuum et terreni culmine imperii ad regnum trnum transtulsti: te supplices exormus; ut, sicut illum, grati tu ubertte prvntum, illecebras sculi superare fecsti, ita nos fcias, ejus imitatine, mundi hujus blandimnta vitare, et ad te puris mntibus pervenre. Per Dminum nostrum.

O GOD, who didst on this day translate blessed Henry thy Confessor from the height of an earthly empire to thy eternal kingdom; we humbly beseech thee that as, by the fullness of thy preventing grace, thou didst strengthen him to overcome the enticements of this life, so thou wouldst enable us to shun, by his example, the blandishments of the world, and with pure hearts to come unto thee. Through our Lord.

text:list-item.text:h: July 16 - Our Lady of Mount Carmel

office:text.text:p: B. Mari Virg. de Monte Carmelo

If the Commem. of Our Lady of Mount Carmel falls on a Saturday, the Saturday Office of the B.V.M. is said, but at the Benedictus the following antiphon is said, and at all Hours the following Prayer is said.

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Caput tuum * ut Carmelus, et com cpitis tui sicut purpura Regis vincta canlibus, allelja.
Ant. Thy head * is like Carmel, and the hair of thy head as the purple of the king bound in the channel, alleluia.
V. Diffsa est grtia in lbiis tuis.
R. Proptrea benedxit te Deus in trnum.
V. Grace is poured abroad upon your thy lips.
R. Therefore hath God blessed thee for ever.

DEUS, qui beatssim semper Vrginis et Genitrcis tu Mar singulri titulo Carmeli ordinem decorsti: concde proptius; ut, cujus hdie Commemoratinem solemni celebrmus officio, ejus muniti prsidiis, ad gaudia sempitrna pervenre meremur: Qui vivis et regnas.

O GOD, who hast honoured the Carmelite Order with the special title of the Order of the most blessed ever-Virgin Mary, thy Mother; mercifully grant that, as we this day celebrate her commemoration with a solemn office, so we may be defended by her protection, and be found worthy to attain to everlasting joys. Who livest and reignest.
Ant. Euge, serve bone * et fidlis, quia in pauca fusti fidlis, supra multa te consttuam, intra in gudium Dmini tui.
Ant. Well done, good servant, * and faithful, because thou hast been faithful over a few things, enter thou into the joy of thy Lord.
V. Justum dedxit Dminus per vias rectas.
R. Et ostndit illi regnum Dei.
V. The Lord conducted the just through the right ways.
R. And showed him the kingdom of God.
DEUS, qui nos beti Alxii Confessris tui annua solemnitate ltificas: concde proptius; ut, cujus nataltia colimus, tiam actines imitemur. Per Dminum.
O GOD, who rejoicest us by the yearly solemnity of blessed Alexius thy Confessor; mercifully grant that, as we celebrate his festival, we may also imitate his actions. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui sanctum Camillum, ad animrum in extrmo agone luctntium subsidium, singulri carittis prrogativa decorsti: ejus, qusumus, meritis spritum nobis tu dilectinis infunde; ut in hora xitus nostri hostem vincere, et ad clestem meremur cornam pervenre. Per Dminum.

O GOD, who didst adorn holy Camillus with a special grace of charity for the relief of souls in their last agony; we beseech thee, by his merits, so to pour into our hearts the spirit of thy love, that at the hour of our death we may overcome the enemy, and be counted worthy to obtain a heavenly crown. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Commem. is made of St. Symphorosa and her Seven Sons, Mm., at Lauds:

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Vestri caplli cpitis * omnes numerti sunt: nolte timre: multis passribus melires estis vos.
Ant. The very hairs of your head * are all numbered; fear not: you are of more value than many sparrows.
V. Exsultbunt Sancti in glria.
R. Ltabntur in cublibus suis.
V. The Saints shall rejoice in glory.
R. They shall be joyful in their beds.
DEUS, qui nos concedis sanctrum Mrtyrum turum Symphoros et filirum ejus nataltia colere: da nobis in trna beatitdine de erum societte gaudre. Per Dminum nostrum.
O GOD, who givest unto us to celebrate the festival of thy holy Martyrs Symphorosa and her sons; grant us to rejoice in their company in eternal happiness. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, qui ad evangelizndum paupribus et ecclesistici ordinis decrem promovndum, betum Vincntium apostolica virtte roborsti: prsta, qusumus; ut, cujus pia merita veneramur, virttum quoque instrumur exemplis. Per Dminum.

O GOD, who didst invigorate blessed Vincent with the strength of an apostle, that he might preach the Gospel to the poor and advance the honour of the ecclesiastical order; grant, we beseech thee, that, as we venerate the merits of his charity, so we may be instructed by the example of his virtues. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Psalms and Antiphons of the current feria.
All else from Common of Confessor non-Bishop.

table:table-cell.text:p: DEUS, misericordirum pater, per merita et intercessinem beti Hieronymi, quem rphanis adjutrem et patrem esse volusti: concde; ut spritum adoptinis, quo flii tui nominmur et sumus, fideliter custodimus. Per Dminum.

O GOD, the Father of mercies, who wast pleased that blessed Jerome should be a helper and father to the fatherless; grant, by his merits and intercession, that we may faithfully preserve the spirit of adoption, whereby we are called, and are, thy sons. Through our Lord.

office:text.text:p: Commemoration is made of St. Margaret, Virgin & Martyr, at Lauds:

table:table-cell.text:p: Ant. Smile est regnum clrum * hmini negotiatri qurnti bonas margartas: invnta una pretisa, dedit mnia sua, et comparvit eam.
Ant. The kingdom of heaven is like to * a merchant seeking good pearls: when he finds one pearl of great price, he gives all that he has and buys it.
V. Diffsa est grtia in lbiis tuis.
R. Proptrea benedxit te Deus in trnum.
V. Grace is poured abroad in thy lips.
R. Therefore hath God blessed thee for ever.
INDULGNTIAM nobis, qusumus, Dmine, beta Margarita Virgo et Martyr imploret: qu tibi grta semper exstitit, et mrito castittis, et tu professine virttis. Per Dminum.

MAY BLESSED Margaret thy Virgin and Martyr, we beseech thee, O Lord, implore for us forgiveness; inasmuch as she was ever pleasing unto thee, both by the merit of her chastity and the confession of thy power. Through our Lord.
